Data Scientists - The New Superheroes 

Data science has become one of the hottest jobs of the decade. Lately, a data science role is becoming more popular to see in SOC environments. As you know, some SOC activities, such as threat hunting, involve dealing with large data; this is where data scientists can help.

Figure - zoom in

Data scientists are responsible for building machine learning models that predict and detect attack patterns. They have excellent knowledge of advanced statistics and algorithms. Data science requires a good understanding of business coupled with excellent technical skills.

Data analysts are good at mathematics and have decent analytic and writing skills. Sometimes they are called statisticians. During their mission, they use a various number of tools like:

  • Microsoft Office Excel: is a spreadsheet developed by Microsoft for many operating systems.
  • R Language: is a programming language used for statistical computing and graphics supported by the R Foundation for Statistical Computing.
  • Wolfram Alpha: is a computational knowledge engine or answer engine developed by Wolfram Alpha LLC.


Some of the major technologies you will see in organizations performing data science are:

  • MapReduce: allows big data to be divided into data chunks and processed distributedly later. Data could be structured or unstructured.
  • Cloudera: Cloudera Data Science & Engineering provides a lot of data engineering tasks.
  • SQL Servers: are relational database management systems developed by Microsoft.
  • Cassandra:  is a free and open-source distributed NoSQL database management system designed to handle large amounts of data across many commodity servers, providing high availability with no single point of failure.
  • Apache HBase: is an open-source, non-relational, distributed database written in java.
  • MongoDB: open-source, cross-platform, document-oriented, and NoSQL database program.
  • Oracle Data Warehouse:  is an optimized Oracle Exadata infrastructure for the data warehouse.
  • Apache Hadoop: a collection of open-source software utilities that facilitates using a network of many computers to solve problems involving massive amounts of data and computation.
  • Apache Spark: is an open-source unified analytics engine for large-scale data processing.


The HELK is a real-world example, an open-source project used for threat hunting built based on some previously discussed technologies.

According to The HELK:

"The Hunting ELK or simply the HELK, is one of the first open-source hunt platforms with advanced analytics capabilities such as SQL declarative language, graphing, structured streaming, and even machine learning via Jupyter notebooks and Apache Spark over an ELK stack. This project was developed primarily for research, but its flexible design and core components can be deployed in larger environments with the right configurations and scalable infrastructure."
